To mitigate the issues with the gap present in the first iteration, an alternative unit panel geometry was chosen. After consulting with the team and conducting further research the geometry shown in *@2-thick-panel-geometry* was chosen to base the computational model around. This geometry utilises an axis shift method to ensure that the thick panel geometry can be folded without creating a gap *@offset_geometry*. It was observed that each side of the panel formed an L shape and that along each straight line, the geometry itself could be modelled as a series of alternating L shaped panels. These panels could later be converted into a three dimensional structure by connecting the segments of the panels in parallel lines together with faces.

